Phenomic selection with NIRS

This hands-on session will demonstrate the steps for making phenomic predictions using Near-Infrared Spectroscopy (NIRS) data. It will include exploring the NIRS data, applying different preprocessing methods, creating a relationship matrix to use in a BLUP model for predictions, and comparing the results with genomic prediction.

The data for this demo comes from a subset of 90 individuals from a diversity panel of inbred lines. For the complete dataset, refer to: https://github.com/Resende-Lab/Graciano_skNIR_Phenomic_Seleciton/.

The mutations used in sweet corn production, sugary1 (su1) and shrunken2 (sh2) genes, are indicated by the variable “mu”. These genes impact endosperm starch biosynthesis and are responsible for increased sugar content in sweet corn relative to field corn.

Preprocessing NIRS data

The spectra absorbance is related to the concentration of the chemical composition of the sample, but external factors independent of sample composition, such as temperature, can influence the measurement. To deal with external effects, preprocessing can be applied. The methods that are usually used include Standard Normal Variate, Multiplicative Scatter Correction, Detrend, and derivatives. Let’s apply the Standard Normal Variate, which centers and scales the spectra, and the first derivative to reduce noise and correct baseline shifts.

## Transforming data for the next steps
NIRS_2020= NIRS%>%filter(year=="2020")  # Selecting a specific year
NIRS_matrix= as.matrix(NIRS_2020[,c(4:773)])
row.names(NIRS_matrix)= NIRS_2020$genotype

#### Plotting raw spectra
wavelengths<-seq(910,1679,by=1)
matplot(wavelengths,t(NIRS_matrix),lty=1,pch=","
        ,xlab="Wavelength (nm)",ylab="Absorbance",
        main="Raw Spectra"
)

#### Standard normal variate (center and scale)
NIRS_SNV=t(scale(t(NIRS_matrix)))
matplot(wavelengths,t(NIRS_SNV),lty=1,pch=","
        ,xlab="Wavelength (nm)",ylab="Absorbance",
        main="Standard normal variate"
)

### 1st derivative 
NIRS_SNV_1D <- savitzkyGolay(NIRS_SNV, m=1, p=2, w=37) 
dim(NIRS_SNV)
## [1]  90 770
dim(NIRS_SNV_1D) ## the savitzkyGolay remove waveleanghts from the borders
## [1]  90 734
colnames(NIRS_SNV_1D[,c(1,734)])
## [1] "X928"  "X1661"
matplot(928:1661,t(NIRS_SNV_1D),lty=1,pch=","
        ,xlab="Wavelength (nm)",ylab="Absorbance",
        main="Standard normal variate"
)

Exploring the data

Estimate the variance components

Considering each wavelength as a trait, incorporating a fixed effect of year in which kernels were harvested and a random effect for genotype by year interaction to estimate the variance components for each wavelength.

# Creating objects to store the values
GenomicVariance = rep(NA, 734)
GxeVariance= rep(NA, 734)
ResidualVariance= rep(NA, 734)
##loop for all the wavelengths
for (i in 1:734) {
  Nirs.data= data.frame(NIRS[,c("genotype","year")],trait= rbind(NIRS_SNV_1D,NIRS_SNV_1D.2)[,i])
  #blup
  model <- mmer(trait~ year,
                random = ~genotype+ genotype:year,
                rcov= ~ units,
                data =Nirs.data)
  GenomicVariance[i] <- summary(model)$varcomp[1,1]
  GxeVariance[i] <- summary(model)$varcomp[2,1]
  ResidualVariance[i] <- summary(model)$varcomp[3,1]
}
##getting as proportion
PropGenomicVariance <- GenomicVariance/(GenomicVariance+GxeVariance+ResidualVariance)*100
PropGxEVariance <- GxeVariance/(GenomicVariance+GxeVariance+ResidualVariance)*100

##plot the variance
par(mar=c(4, 4, 4, 4))
plot(seq(928,1661,by=1), PropGenomicVariance, type="l", xlab="Wavelenght (nm)",
     xlim=c(928, 1662), ylim=c(0, 100), ylab="Variance (%)",cex.axis=0.9 )
polygon(c(928, seq(928,1661,by=1), 1661), c(100, PropGenomicVariance, 100), col = "grey")
#polygon(c(928, seq(928,1661,by=1), 1661),c(0, PropGenomicVariance + PropGxEVariance, 0), col = "#fde725ff")
polygon(c(928, seq(928,1661,by=1), 1661), c(0, PropGenomicVariance, 0), col = "#2a7bbeff")
legend(1535, 20, c("Residual", "Genomic", "GxE"), lty = 0, fill = c("grey", "#2a7bbeff",  "#fde725ff"), cex=0.9)

Computing relationship matrix

###Phenomic
NIRS_SNV_1D= scale(NIRS_SNV_1D, center=T, scale=T) # scale absorbance at each wavelength 
P_matrix<- tcrossprod(NIRS_SNV_1D)/ncol(NIRS_SNV_1D) ##computing the matrix
superheat(P_matrix , left.label = "none", bottom.label = "none")

##Comparing with genomic
superheat(G_mat, left.label = "none", bottom.label = "none")

Prediction model

The GBLUP two-stage, using the BLUEs, follows:

\[ y = \mu + Zg + e \]

where:

  • \(y\) is the vector of BLUEs,
  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean,
  • \(g\) is the vector of genotype effects (assumed to be random), where \(g \sim N(0, G\sigma^2_g)\),
  • \(G\) is a matrix that describes the genomic similarities between pairs of genotypes, and \(\sigma^2_g\) represents the genetic variance,
  • \(e\) is the vector of residuals (random), where \(e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{res})\), and \(\sigma^2_{res}\) is the residual variance.

The \(Z\) refer to the incidence matrices for \(g\), respectively.

The same model used for genomic prediction is also used for phenomic prediction. Therefore, the genomic relationship matrix (\(G\)) is replaced by the phenomic relationship matrix (\(P\)).

Blues$Genotype= as.factor(Blues$Genotype)
##PBlup
mod1 = mmer(Germ~ 1,
            random = ~vsr(Genotype,Gu=P_matrix),
            rcov= ~ units,
            data =Blues)

Cross-validation

source:https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/cross_validation.html

### parameters
n_id = length(Blues$Genotype)
n_model = 2 ## number of models
s=10  #reps for the cross validation

# Creating objects to store the values
y_pred_PS = matrix(NA,n_id,s)
y_pred_GS = matrix(NA,n_id,s)
corr= matrix(NA,s,n_model)
colnames(corr)=c("PS","GS")


##Lopping using cross-validation
for(k in 1:s){
  ## Sets: ####
  set.seed(200+k)                      # Setting the seed
  cv= kfold(n_id, k=5)                # Obtaining cross-validation subset for each fold
  
  ## Models: ####
  for(i in 1:5){  ##for all sets
    
    ### defining test and training population
    data= Blues
    data$Germ[cv==i]= NA
    
    ##PS
    mod1 = mmer(Germ~ 1,
                random = ~vsr(Genotype,Gu=P_matrix),
                rcov= ~ units,
                data =data)
    y_pred_set<-mod1$U$`u:Genotype`$Germ
    y_pred_PS[which(cv==i),k] = y_pred_set[which(cv==i)] # getting prediction for testing population
    
    
    ## Genomic
    mod2 = mmer(Germ~ 1,
                random = ~vsr(Genotype,Gu=G_mat),
                rcov= ~ units,
                data =data)
    y_pred_set<-mod2$U$`u:Genotype`$Germ
    y_pred_GS[which(cv==i),k] = y_pred_set[which(cv==i)] # getting prediction for testing population
    
  }
  
  
  ## accuracy
  corr[k,1] = cor(y_pred_PS[,k],Blues$Germ,use="complete")
  corr[k,2] = cor(y_pred_GS[,k],Blues$Germ,use="complete")
}

Results

# Calculating the accuracy for each model 
colMeans(corr)
##        PS        GS 
## 0.5920730 0.5511528
## plotting
